  <h1>How Rideshare Accident Claims Work</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>The three-phase insurance structure</h2><p>Period 0 (app off): driver&rsquo;s personal insurance only. Period 1 (logged in, no ride): contingent $50K/$100K/$25K from Uber/Lyft. Periods 2/3 (accepted ride through drop-off): $1M third-party liability + contingent comprehensive/collision from Uber/Lyft.</p>
  <h2>Filing a claim</h2><p>Report the accident to Uber or Lyft through their app immediately. The rideshare company&rsquo;s insurer will contact you. For Period 2/3 claims, James River (Uber) or the Lyft carrier handles the claim. Get a police report documenting the driver&rsquo;s app status at the time of the accident — this is critical to determining which phase applies.</p>
  <h2>App status documentation</h2><p>The driver&rsquo;s app status at the time of the accident is the most important fact in a rideshare claim. Uber and Lyft maintain internal records of driver status. Your attorney can subpoena these records if the driver or company disputes the phase. Contemporaneous screenshots of the app by passengers are helpful evidence.</p>
  <h2>Multiple defendants</h2><p>Serious rideshare accidents often involve multiple liable parties: the rideshare driver, the rideshare company&rsquo;s insurer, the other driver (if a multi-vehicle accident), and potentially the vehicle manufacturer (product liability). An attorney coordinates the claims against all parties to maximize recovery.</p>
